The Smithsonian Asian Pacific American Center (APAC) commissioned me a while back to write a song about collective healing for a compilation. I love their museums, so I was delighted to contribute. 

The project has released now, called Bravespace - a
compilation of original songs, sounds and meditations created by Asian American women and
non-binary artists and musicians - including my drone + voice track rooted in raag yaman. 

A Salve That Travels Time 

Bravespace offers listeners a refuge for contemplation, grief and growth. Happy to be alongside artists like Low Leaf, Ana Roxanne, MILCK, Holis and more. Read more about it on https://smithsonianapa.org/bravespace

I want to share a part of my process that has been bringing me a lot of joy lately 🥰 in September, I had a mala 📿 designed for myself to accompany me in my voice practice. It has been pretty transformational both for my discipline and self care.

A mala is string of beads or knots, used in meditation. My mala is made of amethyst for healing, and focuses on bringing me strength (for my hand injury which I’ve been dealing with since I got hurt on tour in 2019) and stability to deal with the high rate of change I’ve been experiencing since I quit working in tech and became a full time artist. It also has Tiger eye for luck, Garnet for grounding and Moss agate for good health. The amethyst quartz is also purple which is my favorite color of them all 😌

Taking a step back from the religious and spiritual associations the mala historically has, this device exists in places where people have discovered something really precious to them, that they wish to protect. At the core, it’s a set of stones that carry energy to enable you and guide you, and I was always intrigued by that.

I’m so delighted by how well it’s been working for me over the past 6 months, and wanted to share my discovery with you in case it helps you connect with your own practice in a deeper manner. A nod of gratitude to @mahamala_in in India for working with me and designing such a transformational resource … TY !!! 

🙏✌️ 💛 😘

#energy #protection #healing #riyaaz 🥹

Season VIII: Arushi Jain.

Arushi Jain (@modularprincess) is a modular synthesist, singer, producer, radio host and engineer with an unorthodox vision of a centuries-old tradition – one that’s electronic and resolutely DIY. Her compositions are inspired by Hindustani classical ragas, explored in an aesthetic that is contemporary and current. Her music is a unique reinterpretation of her two contrasting worlds colliding.

Arushi grew up in Delhi, where she was exposed to Indian classical and other regional music from a young age. Later, Arushi moved to California to study Computer Science at Stanford University, where she was introduced to computer generated sounds and synthesis at the Centre for Computer Research in Music and Acoustics (CCRMA). In her music, ancient ragas from North India are re-imagined with the tools and technologies she learnt as a synthesist and technologist in the Bay Area.

Her last album ‘Under the Lilac Sky’ was released on Leaving Records in July 2021, and was named the Guardian’s Global Album of the month. Her work has been featured on Pitchfork, Bandcamp, Boiler Room, Ableton, Resident Advisor, FACT, Crack, DJMag, and more. Arushi is the founder of GHUNGHRU, a radio series and record label, and is a resident at NTS Radio and boxout.fm.

Modular synthesist, singer and producer Arushi Jain (@modularprincess) brought her hypnotic re-imaginations of ancient ragas from North India to Phoenix Central Park as part of Season VIII.

Jain brings an unorthodox vision to a centuries-old tradition – one that’s electronic and resolutely DIY. Her compositions are inspired by Hindustani classical ragas, explored in an aesthetic that is contemporary and current. Two sittings of lucky ticket holders were able to experience her unique reinterpretation of two contrasting worlds colliding within the depths of The Nest. Jain mesmerised audiences with her experimental dreamy soundscapes, including some from her debut album ‘Under the Lilac Sky’. Composed for the sunset, these tracks truly came to life in the glow of The Nest as Jain created beautiful sounds from her complex synthesisers.

30 🎂☺️🎉🎈

i am entering the new decade with the promise to see all of myself — the beautiful and the ugly — with honesty.

my intentions 

i will act on my power. the way i live life today is a choice, and with choice comes the power to keep what i love and change what i don’t. i will act on my choices. 

i will expand my artistic practice to new levels of expression with care, patience and love. i will teach myself how to. i will learn new skills and i will be unafraid. 

i will relearn how to be with others — isolation has been a big part of my 20s in big city america, but i don’t believe this is how we are meant to live. we are meant to live in community. i will relearn how to live and be in love. 

i will nourish family, friends, collaborators, supporters, and strangers with my kindness, curiosity, and laughter.

i will practice forgiveness in a way that requires me to respect myself always. 

i will strengthen my body and mind, drink water, cook with gratitude, read with focus, listen with intention. i will challenge my inner critic to become more accepting.

i truly believe that i am meant to have a non linear path and i cherish the opportunity to have that. it is difficult but i pick no other life. 

i am thrilled to be here 🥰
i have entered my decade of delight 🥲

On the screen, you can see a visual performance by UIUC’s National Center for Supercomputing Applications Advanced Visualization Lab, who work with celebrated scientists to visualize science research for IMAX, planetariums, museums so that normal people can realize how cool science is :) 

It’s fun to work with people who love what they do, this was one of those times. Swipe for a closer look at the visualization of the sun behind me. The lab monitored and analyzed live audio from my synthesizer to modulate the video footage in real time.

The lab uses machine learning and interactive visuals to render 3d visuals of medical, genomic, hubble telescope and other space data - they’ve worked with leo di caprio, toni myers, Nasa! and also release open source visualization tools…so cool 🥰

I made an EOTY mix for CRACK of music from 2023 that I love. 

I spent a lot of time this year up in the air. Airplanes are a time of self confession for me, I cry there. The solitude persists despite an overfull passenger cabin, welcoming an internal quiet. The undulations in air pressure, bass drone of the engine, and dizzying distance from earth encourages external waves of emotion. In between now and when I’m back on land, I have an opportunity to release, and ready myself to be replenished. These moments are delicate, not unlike the music I chose for this mix.
